04833nam a22007215i 9781400889716DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20182018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008897167 a10.23943/97814008897162doi  a(DE-B1597)501136  a(OCoLC)1029489311  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJV246 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a320.96/09/0452231 aMamdani, Mahmood, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCitizen and Subject :bContemporary Africa and the Legacy of Late Colonialism /cMahmood Mamdani. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Culture/Power/History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Thinking through Africa's Impasse -- tThe structure of power -- tDecentralized Despotism -- tIndirect Rule: the Politics of Decentralized Despotism -- tCustomary law: the Theory of Decentralized Despotism -- tThe Native Authority and the Free Peasantry -- tThe anatomy of resistance -- tThe Other Face of Tribalism: Peasant Movements in Equatorial Africa -- tThe Rural in the Urban: Migrant Workers in South Africa -- tConclusion: Linking the Urban and the Rural -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn analyzing the obstacles to democratization in post- independence Africa, Mahmood Mamdani offers a bold, insightful account of colonialism's legacy--a bifurcated power that mediated racial domination through tribally organized local authorities, reproducing racial identity in citizens and ethnic identity in subjects. Many writers have understood colonial rule as either "direct" (French) or "indirect" (British), with a third variant--apartheid--as exceptional. This benign terminology, Mamdani shows, masks the fact that these were actually variants of a despotism. While direct rule denied rights to subjects on racial grounds, indirect rule incorporated them into a "customary" mode of rule, with state-appointed Native Authorities defining custom. By tapping authoritarian possibilities in culture, and by giving culture an authoritarian bent, indirect rule (decentralized despotism) set the pace for Africa; the French followed suit by changing from direct to indirect administration, while apartheid emerged relatively later. Apartheid, Mamdani shows, was actually the generic form of the colonial state in Africa. Through case studies of rural (Uganda) and urban (South Africa) resistance movements, we learn how these institutional features fragment resistance and how states tend to play off reform in one sector against repression in the other. The result is a groundbreaking reassessment of colonial rule in Africa and its enduring aftereffects. Reforming a power that institutionally enforces tension between town and country, and between ethnicities, is the key challenge for anyone interested in democratic reform in Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aApartheidzAfrica. 0aColonieszAfricaxAdministration. 0aDemocracyzAfrica. 0aDespotismzAfrica. 0aIndigenous peopleszAfrica. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aMamdani, Mahmood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.23943/9781400889716zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400889716423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400889716/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aE